If we have learnt one thing from COVID, it is that we need to reform European healthcare systems.

Europe needs to step up its game regarding e-health practices. E-health would allow better cooperation between Member States, sharing of information and a huge gain of time! It would also help to prevent insurance fraud by keeping a centralised record of a patient’s medical history. This could be done by:

👉 Ensuring patients’ records and their clinical histories can be easily shared among hospitals and general practitioners;

👉Implement transnational e-prescription policies to ensure easy and secure access to prescribed medication for citizens that live, work or otherwise, are abroad;

👉 Developing a public e-booking system for specialists to reduce costly waiting lists, as it already exists for private healthcare insurance;

👉 Developing innovative e-health platforms, with as video consultations and points of contact for general and mental health consultations. 

Emerging technologies such as blockchain ledgers can support the development of these digital services. How would you suggest we develop e-health in Europe? 

We hope you liked our healthcare summer series. Please tell us in the comment what you have learnt from our posts and what is your favourite health reform!
